{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489279"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:11:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:11:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"625"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/625"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.1,0.63,0.12,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49159"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/625"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"9587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43804"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49159"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of fatigue and arthralgia. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus (diet-controlled) and hypertension. He does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker and denies any illicit drug use. He drinks three to four standard drinks of alcohol every night and has done so for about 20 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Brownish-grey pigmentation is noted over his face, neck and forearms. There is fullness of the right upper quadrant on examination of the abdomen. His chest is clear on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EALP: 188 U/L (40-130)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EALT: 124 U/L (5-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAST: 90 U/L (5-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGGT: 167 U/L (5-50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBilirubin: 28 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFerritin: 1200 \u00b5g/L (30-250)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIron: 41 \u00b5mol/L (8-30)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETransferrin: 1.66 g/L (2.0-3.6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETransferrin saturation: 58% (20-50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis C RNA level","Ceruloplasmin level","HFE gene testing","Liver biopsy","Fibroscan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s history, examination findings, and blood test results raise significant suspicion for haemochromatosis, a disorder of iron overload in which iron deposits in tissues including the liver (hepatomegaly progressing to cirrhosis), skin (pigmentation), pancreas (diabetes), heart (congestive cardiac failure), joints (arthropathy), and gonads (hypogonadism). His bloodwork confirms iron overload by revealing significant elevations in ferritin (a marker of bodily iron stores) and transferrin saturation (this iron transport protein having become oversaturated through exposure to high iron levels), strongly suggesting but not absolutely confirming haemochromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemochromatosis is an inherited disorder that arises from a mutation in the \u003Cstrong\u003EHFE gene\u003C/strong\u003E (the most common mutation is termed C282Y), which encodes a regulatory protein for iron haemostasis. Symptoms typically onset between 40 - 60 years of age. Genetic testing has become widely available as a confirmatory test and is a cornerstone for both diagnosis and screening of family members in cases where abnormal ferritin and/or transferrin saturation levels have been identified. \u003Cstrong\u003ELiver biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E also has an important role in ascertaining the presence and severity of liver cirrhosis for the purposes of prognostication, and may be indicated as a future investigation in this case due to the patient\u0027s alcohol intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUncommonly, iron overload can occur as a secondary phenomenon in the context of iron-loading anaemias (e.g. thalassaemia, sideroblastic, transfusional), and chronic liver disease (e.g. hepatitis C, advanced cirrhosis). This patient\u0027s normal haemoglobin and only mildly deranged liver enzymes do not suggest either of these groups of conditions. Furthermore, ferritin elevations in alcoholic liver disease are typically less pronounced (up to 500\u00b5g/L versus over 1000\u00b5g/L in hereditary disease).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of haemochromatosis is focussed on removing excess iron which, notably, is best achieved through regular phlebotomy (and so is a modern indication for blood-letting!). Avoiding alcohol is imperative as it increases the risk of cirrhosis in haemochromatosis ten-fold, and patients are counselled to avoid supplements containing iron or vitamin C (which increases intestinal iron uptake).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis C RNA level\u003C/strong\u003E testing would be appropriate if there was suspicion of hepatitis C infection, which can cause elevated ferritin levels. However, the patient\u0027s history and examination findings are more suggestive of haemochromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeruloplasmin level\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose Wilson\u0027s disease, another inherited disorder of metal metabolism. However, Wilson\u0027s disease typically presents with liver disease and neurological symptoms, and is characterized by copper accumulation rather than iron overload.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroscan\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-invasive method to assess liver fibrosis. While it may be useful in monitoring the progression of liver disease in haemochromatosis, it is not the most appropriate next step in confirming the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HFE gene testing is standard practice for the diagnosis of haemochromatosis and screening of family members."],"references":["Olynyk K, Ramm GA. Hemochromatosis. N Engl J Med 2022; 387:2159-70."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"625"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34244"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-24T13:49:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-24T13:49:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"625"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49159"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updated